  "texts": [
    "Since g is the lift of g, and π 1 (B) is the group of deck transformations of the covering M → M, it is clear that g is π 1 (B)-invariant, regardless of the symmetries of g. On the other hand, let {U i } be a bundle atlas of M with constant transition functions into Aut(N), and let { Ûi } be the corresponding bundle atlas for M. Since the covering map Ûi → U i is N-equivariant, the N-action on Ûi is g-isometric if and only if the N-action on U i is g-isometric, and the proposition follows.",
    "□Given an invariant metric g on M, there is a unique metric g B on B such that π: M → B is a Riemannian submersion.",
    "We also get a connection H:= V ⊥, and an invariant bundle metric g| V×V on the vertical distribution.",
    "The holonomy of g is by definition the holonomy of the connection H (Definition 2.7).In this context, Proposition 2.12 yields:Proposition 2.14.",
    "An invariant metric g on M is determined by the data (g B, H, h), where: (i) g B is a Riemannian metric on the base B, (ii) H = (ker dπ) ⊥ is a connection, and(iii) h is a bundle metric on adM."
